VALUES
(43, 16, 1, 60, 2, 8, 8, 'that ye should not be offended', 'Offense and Stumbling', 'This connection highlights the theme of offense in both passages. John 16:1 speaks of not being offended, while 1 Peter 2:8 refers to a stone of stumbling and offense.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 1, 40, 13, 21, 21, 'that ye should not be offended', 'Connection of Offense in Faith', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being ''offended'' in the face of challenges. John 16:1 encourages believers to avoid offense, while Matthew 13:21 illustrates how tribulation can lead to offense.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 1, 40, 26, 31, 33, 'that ye should not be offended', 'Connection of Offense in Faith', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being ''offended'' due to Jesus'' actions. In John, Jesus prepares his disciples to avoid offense, while in Matthew, he predicts their offense that night. This connection highlights the struggle of faith amidst impending trials.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 1, 43, 15, 18, 27, 'that ye should not be offended', 'Connection of Persecution and Comfort', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of persecution faced by Jesus and his followers. The warning in John 16:1 about not being offended relates to the preceding discussion in John 15:18-27 about the world''s hatred and the promise of the Comforter.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 1, 43, 16, 4, 4, 'these things have I spoken unto you', 'Connection of Warning and Reminder', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of Jesus'' words to prevent offense and to prepare the disciples for future events. The mention of ''these things'' in both verses indicates a continuity in the message being conveyed.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 1, 45, 14, 21, 21, 'not be offended', 'Offense and Brotherhood', 'This connection highlights the theme of being offended in both passages. John 16:1 speaks of not being offended, while Romans 14:21 warns against actions that may cause a brother to be offended.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 1, 50, 1, 10, 10, NULL, 'Connection of Offense in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of being ''without offence.'' John 16:1 warns against being offended, while Philippians 1:10 encourages sincerity and lack of offense until Christ''s return.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 2, 43, 9, 22, 22, 'put you out of the synagogues', 'Exclusion from Synagogue', 'Both passages emphasize the consequence of being put out of the synagogues for those who confess Jesus. John 16:2 predicts this persecution, while John 9:22 illustrates the fear of such exclusion among believers.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 2, 44, 26, 9, 11, 'whosoever killeth you will think that he doeth God service', 'Persecution of Believers', 'This connection highlights the theme of persecution faced by early Christians. Both passages emphasize the idea that those who persecute believers, like Saul, believe they are serving God.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 2, 45, 10, 2, 3, 'whosoever killeth you will think', 'Zeal and Misguided Actions', 'This connection highlights the theme of misguided zeal in both passages. In John 16:2, the act of killing is seen as service to God, while Romans 10:2-3 discusses zeal without knowledge, leading to the establishment of one''s own righteousness.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 2, 40, 10, 28, 28, 'whosoever killeth you', 'Fear of Persecution and Death', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of fear in the face of persecution. John 16:2 discusses those who kill believers thinking they serve God, while Matthew 10:28 encourages not to fear those who kill the body, highlighting a contrast between physical death and spiritual consequence.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 2, 44, 22, 3, 4, 'whosoever killeth you will think', 'Persecution of Believers', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of persecution against believers. In John 16:2, the warning about being put out of synagogues and killed reflects the zealous actions described in Acts 22:3-4, where the speaker acknowledges his past persecution of Christians.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 2, 43, 12, 42, 42, 'put you out of the synagogues', 'Fear of Exclusion from Synagogue', 'Both passages emphasize the fear of being put out of the synagogue. In John 16:2, the threat of expulsion is linked to persecution, while John 12:42 shows belief in Jesus hindered by this fear.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 2, 66, 6, 9, 9, 'whosoever killeth you will think', 'Persecution for Faith', 'This connection highlights the theme of persecution faced by believers. Both passages emphasize the suffering of those who testify for God, with John 16:2 indicating that they will be killed, and Revelation 6:9 showing the souls of those slain for their testimony.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 3, 43, 15, 21, 21, NULL, 'Connection of Persecution for Faith', 'Both passages emphasize that persecution will occur because of a lack of knowledge of God. The phrase ''know not'' links the two verses, highlighting the reason behind the actions taken against believers.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 3, 43, 17, 25, 25, 'not known the Father', 'Knowledge of the Father', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of knowing the Father. In John 16:3, the lack of knowledge about the Father leads to persecution, while John 17:25 highlights that the world has not known the Father, contrasting with Jesus'' knowledge of Him.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 3, 53, 1, 8, 8, NULL, 'Knowledge of God and Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of not knowing God. John 16:3 refers to those who do not know the Father or Jesus, while 2 Thessalonians 1:8 speaks of vengeance on those who know not God. This connection highlights a theme of accountability based on knowledge of God.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 3, 53, 2, 10, 12, 'not known the Father, nor me', 'Connection of Knowledge and Truth', 'This connection highlights the theme of knowing God and the truth. Both passages emphasize the consequences of not knowing the Father and rejecting the truth, leading to spiritual deception and judgment.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 3, 62, 3, 1, 1, 'because they have not known the Father', 'Connection of Knowledge and Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of knowledge of God and its implications for identity. In John 16:3, the lack of knowledge about the Father leads to persecution, while 1 John 3:1 highlights that the world does not recognize believers because it did not know Him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 3, 42, 10, 22, 22, 'not known the Father, nor me', 'Knowledge of the Father and Son', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of knowing the Father and the Son. John 16:3 states that those who persecute believers do so because they do not know the Father or the Son, while Luke 10:22 highlights that true knowledge of the Father and Son is revealed by the Son.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 3, 46, 2, 8, 8, 'have not known the Father, nor me', 'Knowledge of the Father and Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of ignorance regarding the Father and Christ. Both passages emphasize that a lack of knowledge leads to significant consequences, such as persecution and the crucifixion.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 4, 43, 14, 29, 29, NULL, 'Forewarning for Belief', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of foretelling events to strengthen belief. They highlight the idea that prior knowledge of events serves to reinforce faith when those events occur.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 4, 41, 13, 23, 23, 'that when the time shall come', 'Foretelling and Remembrance', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of foretelling events to prepare the disciples. John 16:4 speaks of remembering what was foretold, while Mark 13:23 highlights that all things have been foretold.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 4, 43, 13, 19, 19, NULL, 'Foretelling and Belief', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of foretelling events to strengthen belief. John 16:4 speaks of remembering warnings given earlier, while John 13:19 highlights telling beforehand to foster faith.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 4, 40, 9, 15, 15, NULL, 'Presence and Absence of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' presence and absence. In John 16:4, Jesus prepares his disciples for a time when he will no longer be with them, paralleling Matthew 9:15, where he speaks of the days when the bridegroom will be taken away.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 4, 40, 24, 25, 25, NULL, 'Forewarning of Future Events', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of prior warnings given by Jesus. John 16:4 states that Jesus told his disciples things to remember later, while Matthew 24:25 reiterates that he has informed them beforehand.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 4, 23, 41, 22, 23, 'that when the time shall come', 'Connection of Foretelling Events', 'This connection highlights the theme of foretelling future events. Both passages emphasize the importance of remembering prior warnings and understanding what is to come.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 4, 41, 2, 19, 19, 'I was with you', 'Presence of the Bridegroom', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of Jesus'' presence. In John 16:4, Jesus indicates that his teachings are meant to prepare them for a time when he will no longer be with them, while Mark 2:19 highlights that fasting is not appropriate while the bridegroom is present.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 5, 43, 13, 36, 36, 'Whither goest thou?', 'Connection of Departure Questions', 'This connection highlights the theme of questioning Jesus about his departure. In both passages, the phrase ''Whither goest thou?'' is central to the disciples'' concern regarding Jesus'' journey.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 5, 43, 7, 33, 33, NULL, 'Jesus'' Departure Announcement', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' impending departure to the one who sent him. This connection highlights the continuity of his mission and the significance of his return to the Father.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 5, 49, 4, 7, 11, 'I go my way to him that sent me', 'Ascension and Gifts Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of Christ''s ascension and the subsequent giving of gifts to believers. In John 16:5, Jesus speaks of going to the one who sent him, which aligns with Ephesians 4:7-11''s focus on the gifts given after his ascension.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 5, 58, 1, 3, 3, 'I go my way to him that sent me', 'Departure and Ascension Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' departure as mentioned in John 16:5, where he speaks of going to the one who sent him. Hebrews 1:3 emphasizes his exaltation after purging sins, indicating his return to the divine presence.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 5, 58, 12, 2, 2, 'him that sent me', 'Connection of Jesus'' Departure and Authority', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' journey to the Father and his ultimate authority. In John 16:5, Jesus speaks of going to the one who sent him, while Hebrews 12:2 emphasizes his position at the right hand of God, affirming his role as the author and finisher of faith.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 6, 43, 14, 1, 1, 'sorrow hath filled your heart', 'Connection of Troubled Hearts', 'Both passages emphasize the state of the heart. In John 16:6, sorrow fills the heart, while John 14:1 encourages not to let the heart be troubled.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 6, 42, 24, 17, 17, 'sorrow hath filled your heart', 'Expressions of Sorrow', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of sadness experienced by the disciples. In John, their sorrow is a direct response to Jesus'' words, while in Luke, the disciples are described as sad during their conversation.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 6, 43, 16, 20, 22, 'sorrow hath filled your heart', 'Connection of Sorrow and Joy', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of sorrow transforming into joy. In John 16:6, the disciples'' hearts are filled with sorrow, which is later contrasted with the joy that follows in John 16:20-22. This connection highlights the emotional journey from grief to rejoicing.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 6, 43, 20, 11, 15, 'sorrow hath filled your heart', 'Connection of Sorrow and Weeping', 'This connection highlights the theme of sorrow in both passages. In John 16:6, Jesus acknowledges the sorrow in the hearts of His disciples, while in John 20:11-15, Mary expresses her sorrow through weeping at the tomb.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 6, 42, 22, 45, 45, 'sorrow hath filled your heart', 'Connection of Sorrow in Prayer', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of sorrow affecting the disciples. In John, their hearts are filled with sorrow, while in Luke, they sleep due to sorrow, indicating a shared emotional struggle.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 6, 43, 14, 27, 28, 'sorrow hath filled your heart', 'Connection of Sorrow and Peace', 'This connection highlights the transition from sorrow to peace. In John 16:6, the disciples'' sorrow is acknowledged, while John 14:27-28 offers reassurance of peace, encouraging them not to be troubled.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 7, 43, 14, 26, 26, 'the Comforter will not come unto you', 'Connection of the Comforter', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Comforter, identified as the Holy Ghost, in teaching and reminding the disciples. John 16:7 indicates that the Comforter will come after Jesus departs, while John 14:26 describes the Comforter''s teaching function.', 'theme', 0.573, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 7, 43, 14, 16, 17, 'the Comforter will not come unto you', 'Connection of the Comforter', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Comforter, highlighting that the Spirit of truth will come after Jesus departs. This connection underscores the necessity of Jesus'' departure for the Comforter to be sent.', 'theme', 0.46799999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 7, 44, 2, 33, 33, 'the Comforter will not come unto you', 'Connection of the Holy Spirit', 'This connection highlights the promise of the Comforter in John 16:7 and the fulfillment of that promise in Acts 2:33. Both passages emphasize the sending of the Holy Spirit as a significant event following Jesus'' departure.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 7, 42, 24, 49, 49, 'the Comforter will not come unto you', 'Promise of the Comforter', 'Both passages emphasize the sending of the Comforter and the promise of power. John 16:7 indicates the necessity of Jesus'' departure for the Comforter to come, while Luke 24:49 speaks of waiting for the promise of power from on high.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 7, 44, 1, 4, 5, 'Comforter will not come unto you', 'Promise of the Holy Spirit', 'This connection highlights the promise of the Comforter in John 16:7 and the subsequent baptism with the Holy Ghost in Acts 1:4-5. Both passages emphasize the importance of the Holy Spirit''s coming after Jesus'' departure.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 7, 45, 8, 28, 28, 'Comforter will not come unto you', 'Comfort and Purpose Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine support. In John 16:7, the coming of the Comforter signifies God''s provision, while Romans 8:28 emphasizes that all things work together for good according to His purpose.', 'theme', 0.391, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 7, 49, 4, 8, 13, 'the Comforter will not come unto you', 'Connection of the Comforter and Gifts', 'This connection highlights the transition from Jesus'' departure to the sending of the Comforter, which enables the giving of spiritual gifts. Both passages emphasize the importance of Christ''s ascension in empowering the church through the Holy Spirit.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 8, 44, 2, 37, 37, 'reprove the world of sin', 'Conviction of the Holy Spirit', 'This connection highlights the theme of conviction in both passages. In John 16:8, the Holy Spirit reproves the world of sin, while in Acts 2:37, the listeners are pricked in their heart, indicating a response to that conviction.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 8, 65, 1, 15, 15, 'judgment', 'Judgment and Conviction Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of judgment and the conviction of ungodly actions. John 16:8 speaks of reproving the world of sin and judgment, while Jude 1:15 focuses on executing judgment and convincing the ungodly of their deeds.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 8, 38, 12, 10, 10, 'reprove the world of sin', 'Connection of Sin and Mourning', 'This connection highlights the themes of sin and mourning. In John 16:8, the reproof of sin leads to a recognition of wrongdoing, while Zechariah 12:10 speaks of mourning for the one who was pierced, indicating a deep sorrow for sin and its consequences.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 8, 43, 8, 9, 9, 'reprove the world of sin', 'Conviction of Sin and Righteousness', 'This connection highlights the theme of conviction present in both passages. In John 16:8, the Holy Spirit reproves the world of sin, while in John 8:9, those who heard Jesus were convicted by their own conscience.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 8, 44, 16, 29, 30, 'reprove the world of sin', 'Connection of Sin and Salvation', 'This connection highlights the theme of conviction of sin leading to a quest for salvation. In John 16:8, the Holy Spirit reproves the world of sin, while in Acts 16:29-30, the jailer, recognizing his need for salvation, asks what he must do.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 8, 46, 14, 24, 24, NULL, 'Conviction and Judgment in Faith', 'This connection highlights the theme of conviction and judgment present in both passages. John 16:8 speaks of the Holy Spirit reproving the world of sin and judgment, while 1 Corinthians 14:24 describes how an unbeliever is judged and convinced through prophecy.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 8, 43, 8, 46, 46, 'reprove the world of sin', 'Connection of Conviction and Sin', 'This connection highlights the theme of conviction regarding sin. In John 16:8, the Holy Spirit reproves the world of sin, while in John 8:46, Jesus challenges others to convict him of sin, emphasizing the importance of recognizing sinfulness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 9, 43, 15, 22, 25, 'because they believe not on me', 'Connection of Sin and Belief', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of sin in relation to belief in Jesus. John 16:9 states that sin arises from unbelief, while John 15:22-25 discusses how the rejection of Jesus reveals their sinfulness.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 9, 43, 8, 23, 24, 'because they believe not on me', 'Connection of Unbelief and Sin', 'Both passages emphasize the consequence of unbelief, linking it directly to sin. John 16:9 states that sin is due to not believing in Jesus, while John 8:24 warns that dying in sins is a result of not believing that Jesus is who he claims to be.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 9, 41, 16, 16, 16, 'believe not on me', 'Connection of Belief and Salvation', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of belief in relation to salvation. John 16:9 highlights the consequence of unbelief, while Mark 16:16 states that belief is essential for salvation.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 9, 58, 3, 12, 12, 'believe not on me', 'Connection of Unbelief and Sin', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of unbelief leading to sin. John 16:9 highlights sin as a result of not believing in Jesus, while Hebrews 3:12 warns against an evil heart of unbelief that departs from God.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 9, 44, 2, 22, 38, 'Of sin, because they believe not on me;', 'Connection of Sin and Belief', 'This connection highlights the theme of sin linked to unbelief in John 16:9, which is addressed in Acts 2:38 through Peter''s call to repentance and baptism for the remission of sins. Both passages emphasize the necessity of belief in Jesus for forgiveness.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 9, 44, 3, 14, 19, 'Of sin, because they believe not on me;', 'Connection of Sin and Repentance', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of sin linked to unbelief and the need for repentance. John 16:9 highlights sin due to disbelief in Christ, while Acts 3:19 calls for repentance to have sins blotted out.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 9, 58, 10, 28, 29, 'Of sin, because they believe not on me;', 'Connection of Sin and Punishment', 'This connection highlights the theme of sin and its consequences. Both passages emphasize the seriousness of rejecting belief in Christ and the resultant punishment for such actions.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 10, 47, 5, 21, 21, 'of righteousness', 'Righteousness Through Christ''s Sacrifice', 'This connection highlights the theme of righteousness in both passages. John 16:10 refers to righteousness linked to Jesus'' departure, while 2 Corinthians 5:21 emphasizes being made the righteousness of God through Christ''s sacrificial role.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 10, 45, 10, 3, 4, 'of righteousness', 'Righteousness and Christ''s Role', 'This connection highlights the theme of righteousness in both passages. John 16:10 refers to righteousness linked to Christ''s departure, while Romans 10:3-4 discusses ignorance of God''s righteousness and Christ as the fulfillment of the law.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 10, 60, 3, 18, 18, 'of righteousness, because I go to my Father', 'Connection of Righteousness and Suffering', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of righteousness through Christ''s suffering and his return to the Father. John 16:10 mentions righteousness in relation to Christ''s departure, while 1 Peter 3:18 highlights his suffering for the unjust to bring them to God.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 10, 24, 23, 5, 6, 'Of righteousness, because I go to my Father', 'Connection of Righteousness in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of righteousness. John 16:10 refers to righteousness in relation to Jesus'' departure, while Jeremiah 23:5-6 speaks of a righteous Branch who will bring salvation and justice.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 10, 44, 3, 14, 14, 'righteousness, because I go to my Father', 'Connection of Righteousness and Denial', 'This connection highlights the theme of righteousness in John 16:10, where Jesus speaks of His departure to the Father. In Acts 3:14, the denial of ''the Holy One'' contrasts with the righteousness that Jesus embodies, emphasizing the gravity of their choice.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 10, 46, 1, 30, 30, 'of righteousness', 'Connection of Righteousness in Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of righteousness in both passages. John 16:10 refers to righteousness linked to Jesus'' departure, while 1 Corinthians 1:30 identifies Christ as our righteousness.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 10, 50, 3, 7, 9, 'of righteousness, because I go to my Father', 'Righteousness and Loss for Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of righteousness in both passages. John 16:10 speaks of righteousness linked to Jesus'' departure, while Philippians 3:7-9 discusses counting all things as loss to gain the righteousness through faith in Christ.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 11, 43, 12, 31, 31, 'the prince of this world', 'Judgment of the Prince', 'Both passages emphasize the judgment of the prince of this world. John 16:11 states that he is judged, while John 12:31 declares that he will be cast out, highlighting a definitive action against him.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 11, 62, 3, 8, 8, 'the prince of this world is judged', 'Judgment and the Devil''s Works', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment against the devil. Both passages emphasize the defeat of the devil''s influence, with John noting the judgment of the ''prince of this world'' and 1 John stating the purpose of Christ''s manifestation to ''destroy the works of the devil.''', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 11, 43, 14, 30, 30, 'prince of this world', 'Connection of the Prince of This World', 'Both passages emphasize the ''prince of this world,'' highlighting his impending judgment and lack of claim over Jesus. This connection underscores the spiritual authority of Jesus in contrast to the adversary.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 11, 51, 2, 15, 15, 'the prince of this world is judged', 'Judgment of the Prince', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment against spiritual powers. Both passages emphasize the defeat of the ''prince'' and the triumph over ''principalities and powers''.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 11, 58, 2, 14, 14, 'prince of this world is judged', 'Judgment and Power of Death', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment against evil. Both passages refer to the defeat of the devil and the judgment of the prince of this world, emphasizing the victory over death and evil.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 11, 47, 4, 4, 4, 'prince of this world is judged', 'Judgment and the God of This World', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment against the ''prince of this world'' and the ''god of this world.'' Both passages emphasize the spiritual blindness caused by this figure, indicating a direct link between judgment and the hindrance of belief.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 16, 11, 23, 49, 24, 26, 'prince of this world is judged', 'Judgment and Deliverance Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of judgment against oppressors. John 16:11 speaks of the judgment of the ''prince of this world,'' while Isaiah 49:24-26 assures deliverance from the mighty and oppressors. This connection highlights the ultimate victory of God over evil.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
